results.abstract: Former Apollo astronaut Rusty Schweikert is among experts who are concerned by lack of attention paid to possible dangers of incoming asteroids; NASA is trying to track large pieces of space matter that could devastate entire regions, but budget constraints have slowed its efforts to identify them by 2009; photo; maps (M)

headline.main: Maybe Chicken Little Wasn't Paranoid After All

results.snippet: “Civilization killers” are one thing, but when it comes to earth-bound objects, smaller rocks matter too.
results.lead_paragraph: THE Earth is pockmarked with the evidence of ancient collisions -- huge craters blasted into its surface by asteroids or comets. One such object, striking 65 million years ago in the Yucat√°n in Mexico, is believed by some experts to be linked to the demise of the dinosaurs. For a decade, NASA has been busy trying to identify what else is headed this way, particularly those potential ''civilization killers'' of 1 kilometer (.62 miles) or more in diameter that have orbits coming within 30 million miles of the Earth's -- too close for comfort by space standards.

results.abstract: Carlton C Allen, Johnson Space Center Lunar Sample Laboratory Facility astromaterials curator, discusses continuing research on 842 pounds of rocks and soil brought back to earth after six Apollo missions to moon; findings have shed light on early universe and geography of moon; photos (L)
results.snippet: Decades after the Apollo astronauts brought the first Moon rocks back to Earth, they are still providing scientists with new secrets.
results.lead_paragraph: In the lab, the Moon rocks look nondescript -- dark gray basalt, a whitish mineral called anorthosite and mixtures of the two with crystals thrown in. Yet nearly 40 years after the Apollo astronauts brought the first rocks back to Earth, these pieces of the Moon are still providing scientists with new secrets from another world. ''We call this one the 'genesis' rock, because it was formed close to the time the Moon solidified about 4.5 billion years ago,'' said Carlton C. Allen, pointing to a light-colored stone about the size and shape of a large artist's eraser, resting inside a glove box filled with inert nitrogen gas.

byline.original: By CAROLINE BROTHERS  and MICHELINE MAYNARD

results.lead_paragraph: Kensington Palace in London had been hired. The governor of Alabama was set to play host, the astronaut Buzz Aldrin was on the guest list and the leading European aerospace company was to be the toast of the evening. But the Pentagon's decision last week to reopen the $35 billion competition for midair refueling tankers for the United States Air Force cast a pall over Sunday's reception under a lemon-yellow moon in the gardens of the royal residence where the Princess of Wales once lived.

results.snippet: Michelle Obama is sometimes compared to Jacqueline Kennedy, but she may now have something in common with another first lady, Eleanor Roosevelt. Mrs. Roosevelt became an honorary member of the Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority, a historically black...
results.lead_paragraph: Michelle Obama is sometimes compared to Jacqueline Kennedy, but she may now have something in common with another first lady, Eleanor Roosevelt. Mrs. Roosevelt became an honorary member of the Alpha Kappa Alpha sorority, a historically black organization founded in 1908, and the group announced this week at its centennial convention that Mrs. Obama had agreed to join. The sorority said that once Mrs. Obama was formally inducted into the organization, which has 225,000 members, she could not become a member of any of the other ''Divine Nine'' organizations, as black sororities and fraternities are often called. Other honorary members of Alpha Kappa Alpha include the poet Maya Angelou, the late Coretta Scott King and the former astronaut Mae Jemison.

headline.main: Murcer's Jersey Made a Journey to Outer Space

results.snippet: An astronaut and life-long baseball fan takes his dying hero’s jersey on an extraterrestrial journey.
results.lead_paragraph: A friendship of a lifetime began through static. Doug Wheelock loved the Yankees and listened to every game while growing up in the 1960s in Windsor, N.Y., a small town upstate. He would sneak a radio into bed for late games, his mother saying, ''That radio better not be on!''

headline.main: Twin Hopes: Satisfying Movie, Low Cost

results.snippet: The filmmaking duo the Polish brothers established Prohibition Pictures in the spring to address their concerns with production costs and artistic independence.
results.lead_paragraph: IN the sunbaked no-man's land of this city's Warehouse District, behind the facade of the barnlike DC Stages, the filmmaking Polish brothers (''The Astronaut Farmer'') are creating the first of what will be back-to-back comedies. The story line involves a company in the red. The mood of the characters is black. And the palette is relentlessly, unforgivingly brown.
